mapped_songs.comment_text: I was lucky enough to be the recording engineer on this session. Dave Allen (producer of some great Cure albums, Sisters Of Mercy amongst others) was producing. Prior to recording the whole album at Jacobs Studio near Farnham, Hampshire. The band came down to West Side studios in west London to record three songs with Dave Allen. Dave's concept for this project was that the band should all play together and nail the songs live with no overdubs. This proved pretty difficult for the band who weren't seasoned studio pro musicians - I'm not sure how much they'd played live at that point. I think we might have had three weeks - a week per song to record three songs? I remember feeling very sorry for the band because they were just playing the songs over and over and over again and Dave would be saying 'sorry, not quite there yet - try that again'.  I was wondering if Dave would cave in with his concept and do what was normal with this kind of band,  concentrate on getting a good drum recording first and then build up everything on top of that, one instrument and vocal at a time. I don't remember him caving -  if he did, it was not for a long time. I remember a lot of tension in the band because if anyone screwed up we would stop the recording and they would start the song again. I realized though when we started the whole album recording a few weeks or months later, that although it was a very tough approach by Dave, it transformed the band. When they came back to the studio, they were a much tighter, well rehearsed band. I can't remember what the other two songs were that were recorded at the same time as Swamp Thing but this was by far the best song of the session and my favorite on the album. Such amazing guitar riffs and incredible mood.
mapped_songs.ananki_reasoning: The human explicitly mentions this song was recommended in a 'Goth playlist' context and describes a recording session produced by Dave Allen, who is specifically noted for producing 'great Cure albums, Sisters Of Mercy amongst others' - both iconic gothic rock bands. The production approach of recording live with no overdubs was common in gothic rock production. The post title and producer credentials directly establish this as a gothic/goth track.

mapped_songs.song: The Third Man Theme ( Studio Version)
mapped_songs.comment_text: My step-brother and I went to the Texan Theater in Greenville, Texas, in 1949, to watch a movie.  The ticket for entrance was 9 cents, popcorn cost a nickel, cold drink cost a nickel, candy bar cost a nickel, and I still had a penny left over for gum.  The movie?  The Third Man!  I was eight-years-old and sat there entranced throughout the movie, spellbound by the action,  and had a lifetime memory forged by the music.  Anton Karas' zither played in my head for weeks after the show left town.  I'll tell you...when Orson Wells and Joseph Cotton started ascending into the air on that gigantic ferris wheel, I nearly had a heart attack as a kid; I couldn't wait for the carriage to get back down. Whenever Alida Valli appeared in a scene, that zither music slowed down and became so melancholy, it made a lasting impression on me.  And when I saw either Siskell or Ebert (I can't remember which) asked by Johnny Carson on Carson's show what the critics' favorite all-time movie was and the answer came, "The Third Man", it stirred up memories thick as molasses. I loved it then; I love it now--70 years later. That was the best quarter that I have ever spent.
mapped_songs.ananki_reasoning: The human is recalling a vivid childhood memory from 1949 at age 8, watching 'The Third Man' at a theater. The detailed recall of prices (9 cents for a ticket, nickels for treats) and the statement that this created a 'lifetime memory' with the music playing in their head 'for weeks after' demonstrates a deep nostalgic attachment to this song.
